s in their lands, but in the end, the defeat of Catharism in the south of France was achieved through the establishment of the Inquisition and the extension of French royal authority to thearea. While some Occitan noble families survived the crusade, others were destroyed and the behaviour of the crusaders towards the local nobility has often been regarded as rather arbitrary, unconnected to how these families related to each other before 1209. This study takes the case of the Trencavel Viscounts of Béziers and Carcassonne, who were the only members of the higher nobility to lose their lands to the crusade, and argues that an understandingof how the Occitan nobility fared in the crusade years must be based in the context of the politics of the noble society of Languedoc, not only in the thirteenth century but also in the twelfth. ELAINE GRAHAM-LEIGH gained her Ph.D. from the University of London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlbigensesxHistoryzFrance, Southwest. 0aChristian heresiesxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500zFrancezLanguedoc. 0aNobilityxHistoryzFrance, Southern. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAlbigensian Crusade.  aCathar Heretics.  aFrench Royal Authority.  aIndigenous Nobility.  aInquisition.  aLanguedoc Politics.  aNoble Society.  aOccitan Noble Families.  aSouthern France.  aThirteenth Century.  aTrencavel Viscounts.  aTwelfth Century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846154294?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154294/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre